>
  <p class="lede">
    I build the connective tissue between product, engineering and marketing —
    and I've worked from inside each of them.
  </p>

  <p>
    Over fifteen years I've grown from senior software engineer to technical
    lead to product owner to senior product leadership. Today I'm Head of
    Product Marketing and Principal Product Manager at an Australian-owned
    global product company in the Data&nbsp;Risk&nbsp;&amp;&nbsp;Compliance
    space, leading cross-functional teams and partnering with regional sales and
    executives to shape and execute go-to-market strategy.
  </p>

  <p>
    Because I've sat in the engineering chair, the product-owner chair and the
    marketing chair, I can translate an ambiguous, subjective requirement into
    something scoped, estimable, priced and shippable — and then stand behind
    the outcome. I gathered Data Governance needs from many enterprise
    customers, harmonised them into a coherent feature set, and used C4-model
    analysis to drive effort estimation, work breakdown and pricing. I designed
    the <strong>GTM Factory</strong>, a repeatable product-marketing framework
    that compresses time-to-market by running a virtual team deep into
    engineering.
  </p>

  <h2>Applied AI, hands-on</h2>
  <p>
    I prototyped AI capabilities — an AI Asset Description generator and an AI
    Code Explainer — and I design AI-driven automation across product and
    marketing workflows. I work with GenAI models, RAG, prompt engineering, MCP
    and AI agents (Claude, n8n, Zapier), and recently completed an intensive
    six-month GenAI program at IIT Patna.
  </p>

  <h2>Why education</h2>
  <p>
    The thread runs through everything I've done outside work: a Masters in
    Public Administration, editing a student e-journal, coordinating campus
    placements, and volunteering to teach underprivileged children through
    Project Manthan. I'm drawn to the education sector because it's where
    product craft, technology and human outcomes meet most directly — and it's
    where I most want to apply what I build. The EdTech case studies on this
    site are early explorations of exactly that.
  </p>

  <h2>How I think about the work</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Point of view first.</strong> Strategy is a stance, not a status report.</li>
    <li><strong>Discovery to production.</strong> Own the outcome, not the handoff.</li>
    <li><strong>Bias to iterate.</strong> Start small, ship, learn — "Say NO! to Waterfall".</li>
    <li><strong>Bridge the silos.</strong> The best leverage lives between product, engineering and marketing.</li>
  </ul>

</ProseLayout>
